The two most common 5.56 rounds are the 55gr M193 and the 62gr “green tip” M855, both of which are used by the US military. The NATO SS109 62gr steel core “penetrator” bullet is used in the M855 round. The steel penetrator makes it more effective at penetrating hard targets and such.

5.56 ammunition is only to be used in rifles labeled 5.56mm, and must NOT be used in those rifles labeled .223.

title: For Sale:  Finest H&R Topper 58 Single-Shot 410 3" Great Gift! 26 Inch Skeet/Hunt Beginner/Expert
postcontent: This is probably the finest condition H&R single-shot outside of one brand new in the box. Checking over Gunbroker + Armslist listings, I find a couple on the low end at $135 to $145 but they need refinishing, have cracks, are in average condition or have other issues. Even at the $175 to $199 level you find missing sight beads or some in very decent shape at a listed 85% condition. Nothing close to this. This is the perfect shotgun for the younger shooter or newcomer to trap. I shoot only single-shots, from 100 year old Iver Johnsons to several H&R models. This was supposed to be for my daughter, but she went with the 20 gauge I had. At 16, she is not a beginner and she wanted some extra payload in the lead shot. This is why 410 is so perfect for learning and experts, it is the easiest to manage and also requires practice and skill to shoot high scores, both due to its smaller size. This has a 3 inch chamber which gives you the option of using 2.5 inch or 3 inch as there is a difference in recoil and shot payload between the two. The much lower recoil makes all the difference to younger or new shooters, as it is easy to get turned off to shooting with a bruised shoulder. Two or 3 rounds of trap, and even the 410 starts leaving its presence behind for a few days. (I bought PAST shoulder pads for all the kids). The much smaller size is what makes this perfect for everyone, as it is far easier to learn the proper technique when recoil and blast are not excessive and if you learn on a 410, when you step up to a larger size, your hit percentage will fly up as you are now tossing double the amount of pellets. Many women who are smaller statured, also do very well with this caliber (410 is a caliber not a gauge) and size shotgun. For the expert, the 410 is actually the hardest of all to score the highest scores with as it sends a much smaller pellet cloud downrange. It is like shooting at the clay discs with a 22 rifle in my opinion. The model is a Topper 58 and I have a full set of photos available if you ask. Every inch of the metal is deep blued and shiny with no faded areas, scratches or anything but perfect blued steel. The bore is a mirror. The finish on the metal is far superior to many current discount or entry level shotguns as the $220 to $250 range new shotguns are great, but of course they save on finishing. The barrel is 26 inches and the bead is present at the end (several others listed are missing it). The receiver is a case colored finish with a nice range of hues and colors. This is not faded or worn away either as handling over time will do. The action is slick and smooth with NO looseness at all. Releasing the lever results in a crisp click and the barrel lowers from gravity, but does not drop. It is almost like hydraulics as it opens slower. The forend is gloss finished wood and perfect. Perfect as in perfect. The buttstock is 99% condition as there is a mark less than an inch long and a dot nearby that is .25mm and it shows in the photo that I took close-up. It is hard to see for a reason, it is extremely minor. I have bought brand new firearms with more marks on them just from the store putting them together and customers handling them. You can find a decent one for about $30 less if you look, but for that extra $30 you get a shotgun that is truly beautiful and worthy of a gift. I sold a similar condition single action 22 revolver to a guy to be given to his fiancee as a wedding present. You can have a name or date engraved or branded onto the stock pretty inexpensively and make a gift that will be passed down through generations. Teach your child the rules, the safety and the fun of shooting sports, and they will have the pride of owning their own. With pride of ownership comes responsibility and the kind of lessons you can not learn in school. If small game hunting is your thing, a 410 is again, the perfect choice. Lighter to carry in the field and a box of shells is 1/3 the size and weight as 12 gauge. Choked full and that is how the barrel is made, with the choke integrated into the design. No replaceable chokes on this one and at full, it really is like shooting a 22 at the clays. Save enough over a new one to pay for 4 boxes of shells and a couple of trips to the skeet/trap range for you and whoever is lucky enough to receive this gift. I can tell you from experience, the $30 or so you may save getting a lower priced one, will bug you for years, every time you open the case and see faded bluing, scratches in the wood, cracks or any of the imperfections and damage that the others all seem to have. If you are going to keep this or pass it down, or make a gift from it, that little bit you saved over many years is nothing. Ships Fedex Ground,unless USPS Priority is the same or less. Your location will determine that. Local face-to-face sales are the best deal as no shipping, no FFL fees. I will meet you from Boca to Miami if you are local. Shipping will be $28. If Paypal is used for payment, it must be discrete (no mention of firearms) and add $5 which is PART of their fees. I'll take care of the difference
